================================================================================
        pfSense FIREWALL - INSTALLATION & CONFIGURATION GUIDE
        PGCP-ITISS Lab | C-DAC ACTS Pune | pfSense CE 2.6.0
================================================================================

TABLE OF CONTENTS
-----------------
  1. Create Virtual Machine & Install pfSense
  2. Initial Web Console (GUI) Setup
  3. Install Squid Proxy
  4. Configure Squid Proxy
  5. Install SquidGuard
  6. Configure SquidGuard (URL Filtering)
  7. Configure SSL Man-in-the-Middle (HTTPS Inspection)
  8. User-Based Internet Access Control


================================================================================
PHASE 1 : CREATE VIRTUAL MACHINE & INSTALL pfSense
================================================================================

[ VM HARDWARE SETUP IN VMWARE WORKSTATION / PLAYER ]

Step 1 : Open VMware - Create New VM
         Launch VMware Workstation 16 Player.
         Click "Create a New Virtual Machine".

Step 2 : Select Installation Method
         On the wizard choose "I will install the operating system later".
         Click Next.

Step 3 : Choose Guest OS
         Guest OS  --> Linux
         Version   --> Ubuntu 64-bit
         Click Next.
         NOTE: pfSense is FreeBSD-based but Ubuntu 64-bit works fine in VMware.

Step 4 : Name the VM & Set Location
         Virtual machine name : pfsense
         Location             : D:\Virtual Machines\pfsense (or your path)
         Click Next.

Step 5 : Specify Disk Capacity
         Maximum disk size  : 60 GB
         Storage option     : Store virtual disk as a single file
         Click Next.

Step 6 : Review Summary & Finish
         Verify:
           Name            = pfsense
           Hard Disk       = 60 GB
           Memory          = 4096 MB
           Network Adapter = NAT
         Click Finish.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

[ ATTACH ISO & ADD SECOND NETWORK CARD ]

Step 7 : Edit VM Settings - Attach pfSense ISO
         Select the VM --> Click "Edit virtual machine settings"
         Click CD/DVD (SATA)
         Choose "Use ISO image file"
         Browse to the downloaded pfSense-CE-x.x.x-RELEASE.iso file.

Step 8 : Add a Second Network Adapter
         In VM Settings --> Click Add at the bottom
         Select Network Adapter --> Click Finish.

Step 9 : Configure Network Adapters
         pfSense requires exactly 2 NICs:

         Adapter              | VMware Mode | pfSense Role | Purpose
         ---------------------|-------------|--------------|------------------------------
         Network Adapter 1   | NAT         | WAN (em0)    | Internet via host
         Network Adapter 2   | Host-only   | LAN (em1)    | Internal private network

Step 10: Start the VM
         Click OK to close settings.
         Click the green Play button or "Play virtual machine".
         pfSense boot screen will appear.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

[ pfSense INSTALLER WALKTHROUGH ]

Step 11: Accept Copyright Notice
         Wait for Copyright & Distribution screen.
         Press Enter to Accept.

Step 12: Choose Install
         Welcome screen --> "Install" is pre-selected.
         Press Enter (OK).

Step 13: Keymap Selection
         "Continue with default keymap" is highlighted.
         Press Enter.

Step 14: Partitioning - ZFS Configuration
         Default option is Auto (ZFS).
         Press Enter (OK) to proceed.

Step 15: ZFS - Proceed with Installation
         On ZFS Configuration screen select >> Install.
         Press Enter.

Step 16: Virtual Device Type - Stripe
         Select "Stripe - No Redundancy".
         Press Enter (OK).

Step 17: Select Disk
         Press Spacebar to select da0 (VMware Virtual Disk).
         Press Enter (OK).

Step 18: Last Chance Confirmation
         "Last Chance! Are you sure you want to destroy da0?"
         Press Enter to confirm YES.
         WARNING: This erases all data on da0. Fine for VM use.

Step 19: Installation Begins
         Files are fetched and extracted.
         Wait for the progress bar to complete (a few minutes).

Step 20: Manual Configuration Prompt
         "Installation is now finished. Would you like to open a shell?"
         Choose No --> Press Enter.

Step 21: Reboot
         "Installation of pfSense complete! Would you like to reboot?"
         Press Enter (Reboot).
         pfSense will boot into its main console menu.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

[ CONFIGURE LAN IP ADDRESS AFTER BOOT ]

NOTE: After boot pfSense assigns 192.168.1.1/24 to LAN by default.
      We must change this to match the VMnet1 (Host-only) adapter
      range on the Windows host.

Step 22: Find VMnet1 IP on Windows Host
         Open Command Prompt on Windows host and run:
           ipconfig
         Find "VMware Network Adapter VMnet1" and note its IPv4 address.
         Example: 192.168.148.1

Step 23: Set LAN IP on pfSense Console
         In pfSense console menu --> Type 2 --> Press Enter
         ("Set Interface(s) IP Address")

Step 24: Select LAN Interface
         Available interfaces:
           1 = WAN (em0)
           2 = LAN (em1)
         Type 2 --> Press Enter.

Step 25: Enter New LAN IP
         Enter IP in the VMnet1 range.
         Example: 192.168.148.10
         Press Enter.
         WARNING: Do NOT use the same IP as your Windows VMnet1 adapter.

Step 26: Enter Subnet Mask
         Subnet bit count --> Type 24 --> Press Enter
         (24 = 255.255.255.0)

Step 27: Upstream Gateway (LAN only)
         "For a LAN, press Enter for none"
         Just press Enter.

Step 28: IPv6 - Skip
         "Enter the new LAN IPv6 address"
         Press Enter to skip.

Step 29: DHCP Server on LAN?
         "Do you want to enable the DHCP server on LAN? (y/n)"
         Type n --> Press Enter.
         NOTE: In production you would enable DHCP for automatic client IPs.

Step 30: Revert to HTTP?
         "Do you want to revert to HTTP as the webConfigurator protocol? (y/n)"
         Type n --> Press Enter.
         (Keeps HTTPS access to pfSense web console - more secure)

RESULT: LAN IP is now configured.
        pfSense console shows: LAN (lan) --> em1 --> v4: 192.168.148.10/24


================================================================================
PHASE 2 : INITIAL WEB CONSOLE (GUI) SETUP
================================================================================

NOTE: Perform these steps from a SECOND VM (Windows or Linux).
      That VM's NIC must be in Host-only mode with a static IP
      in the same subnet as pfSense LAN (e.g., 192.168.148.20/24).

Step 1 : Open Browser - Navigate to pfSense WebGUI
         Type in browser: https://192.168.148.10
         (Replace with your pfSense LAN IP)
         A self-signed certificate warning appears.
         Click Advanced --> Proceed to site.

Step 2 : Login
         Username : admin
         Password : pfsense   (default credentials)

Step 3 : Setup Wizard - Step 1 (Welcome)
         Click Next on the Welcome to pfSense screen.

Step 4 : Step 2 (Netgate Global Support)
         Click Next.

Step 5 : Step 2 - General Information (DNS & Hostname)
         Field                | Value (Lab Example)
         ---------------------|--------------------
         Hostname             | HQ-pfSense
         Domain               | demo.lab
         Primary DNS Server   | 8.8.8.8
         Secondary DNS Server | 8.8.4.4
         Override DNS         | Checked
         Click Next.

Step 6 : Step 3 - Time Server
         Keep defaults:
           Time server hostname : 2.pfsense.pool.ntp.org
           Timezone             : Asia/Kolkata (or your timezone)
         Click Next.

Step 7 : Step 4 - Configure WAN Interface
         SelectedType : DHCP (keep default for lab)
         Leave MAC Address, MTU, MSS blank.

         Two rules at bottom of page:
         Rule                         | What It Does
         -----------------------------|------------------------------------------
         Block RFC1918 Private Nets   | Blocks 10/8, 172.16/12, 192.168/16 on WAN
         Block Bogon Networks         | Blocks IANA-reserved/unassigned IPs on WAN
         Both are checked by default - LEAVE THEM CHECKED.

         Click Next.

Step 8 : Step 5 - Configure LAN Interface
         LAN IP Address : 192.168.148.10 (already set from console)
         Subnet Mask    : 24
         Keep as is --> Click Next.

Step 9 : Step 6 - Set Admin Password
         Enter a strong new password for admin in both fields.
         Click Next.
         WARNING: Default password is "pfsense". Change it immediately.
                  Using default credentials is a critical security risk.

Step 10: Step 7 - Reload Configuration
         Click Reload. pfSense applies all settings.

Step 11: Step 9 - Check for Updates
         Click "Check for Updates".
         If updates exist they download automatically.
         When done the screen shows "Up to date".

RESULT: pfSense initial GUI setup is complete.
        You should now see the full pfSense Dashboard.


================================================================================
PHASE 3 : INSTALL SQUID PROXY ON pfSense
================================================================================

NOTE: Squid is a high-performance web proxy/caching server. On pfSense
      it intercepts HTTP/HTTPS traffic from LAN clients, enabling
      logging, filtering, and caching.

Step 1 : Navigate to Package Manager
         Top menu --> System --> Package Manager

Step 2 : Click Available Packages Tab
         Click the "Available Packages" tab.

Step 3 : Search for Squid
         Search box --> type: squid --> Click Search
         Three packages appear: LightSquid, squid, squidGuard

Step 4 : Install Squid Package
         Find row where Name = squid (version 0.4.45_9)
         Click the [+ Install] button on the right.

Step 5 : Confirm Installation
         "Confirmation Required to install package pfSense-pkg-squid"
         Click Confirm.

Step 6 : Wait for Installation to Complete
         Package Installer shows real-time log output.
         Downloads and installs approx 13 dependency packages.
         Wait until you see "Success" at the bottom.
         NOTE: Do not close or refresh the page during installation.

RESULT: Squid is now installed.
        Verify under: System --> Package Manager --> Installed Packages


================================================================================
PHASE 4 : CONFIGURE SQUID PROXY
================================================================================

[ STEP A - LOCAL CACHE TAB ]

Step 1 : Open Squid Settings
         Top menu --> Services --> Squid Proxy Server

Step 2 : Go to Local Cache Tab
         Click the "Local Cache" tab.
         Available settings: Hard Disk Cache Size, Cache Location,
         Memory Cache Size.
         For this lab KEEP ALL DEFAULTS.

Step 3 : Save Cache Settings
         Click Save.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

[ STEP B - GENERAL SETTINGS TAB ]

Step 4 : Click General Tab
         Click the "General" tab on the Squid Proxy Server page.

Step 5 : Enable Squid Proxy
         Check the box "Check to enable the Squid proxy".
         IMPORTANT: If unchecked ALL Squid services will be disabled.

Step 6 : Select Proxy Interfaces
         In "Proxy Interface(s)"
         Hold Ctrl and click to select BOTH: LAN and loopback

Step 7 : Check Proxy Port
         Proxy Port = 3128 (default - keep as is)

Step 8 : Enable Access Logging
         Scroll down --> Check "Enable Access Logging" checkbox.
         Log Store Directory defaults to: /var/squid/logs
         WARNING: Do NOT enable if disk space is critically low.

Step 9 : Set Visible Hostname & Admin Email
         Field                  | Example Value
         -----------------------|------------------
         Visible Hostname       | proxy.demo.lab
         Administrator's Email  | admin@demo.lab

Step 10: Save & Start Squid
         Scroll to bottom --> Click Save.
         Squid proxy service starts.
         Restart/Stop buttons appear at top confirming service is running.

RESULT: Squid Proxy is now running on port 3128 on the LAN interface.


================================================================================
PHASE 5 : INSTALL SQUIDGUARD
================================================================================

NOTE: SquidGuard is a URL filter add-on for Squid. It blocks websites
      based on blacklists and target categories. It works as a
      redirector plug-in for Squid.

Step 1 : Go Back to Package Manager
         Top menu --> System --> Package Manager --> Available Packages tab

Step 2 : Search for SquidGuard
         Search box --> type: squid --> Click Search
         Now 2 packages shown (squid is already installed).

Step 3 : Install SquidGuard
         Find "squidGuard" (version 1.16.18_20)
         Click [+ Install].

Step 4 : Confirm Installation
         Click Confirm.
         Wait for installation to complete.
         Final log output shows "Success".

RESULT: SquidGuard installed successfully.


================================================================================
PHASE 6 : CONFIGURE SQUIDGUARD (URL FILTERING)
================================================================================

[ STEP A - GENERAL SETTINGS & BLACKLIST DOWNLOAD ]

Step 1 : Open SquidGuard Settings
         Top menu --> Services --> SquidGuard Proxy Filter

Step 2 : DO NOT Enable SquidGuard Yet
         On General Settings tab - DO NOT check the Enable checkbox yet.
         You must set up Target Categories first.
         CRITICAL: Enabling before creating a Target Category will
                   cause SquidGuard to block ALL traffic.

Step 3 : Enable Blacklist
         Scroll down on General Settings.
         Under "Blacklist options" - Check the "Blacklist" checkbox.

Step 4 : Enter Blacklist URL
         In the "Blacklist URL" field enter:
         https://dsi.ut-capitole.fr/blacklists/download/blacklists_for_pfsense.tar.gz

         This is the UT1 (Universite Toulouse) public blacklist -
         a large community-maintained URL block list.

Step 5 : Click Save
         Scroll to bottom --> Click Save.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

[ STEP B - DOWNLOAD THE BLACKLIST ]

Step 6 : Go to Blacklist Tab
         Click the "Blacklist" tab at the top of the SquidGuard page.

Step 7 : Verify URL & Download
         Confirm the blacklist URL is shown.
         Click the "Download" button.
         Blacklist Update Log shows download progress.
         Wait for "Completed" or "Done" message.
         NOTE: The blacklist archive is large (several hundred MB).
               Download time depends on internet speed.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

[ STEP C - CREATE TARGET CATEGORY ]

Step 8 : Go to Target Categories Tab
         Click the "Target categories" tab.

Step 9 : Click Add
         Click the [+ Add] button on the right side.

Step 10: Configure the Target Category
         Field   | Value
         --------|----------------
         Name    | Allowed_content
         Order   | -- (leave default)
         Log     | Check this checkbox

Step 11: Save the Target Category
         Click Save.
         "Allowed_content" now appears in the list.
         Click Save again on the Target categories list page.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

[ STEP D - ENABLE SQUIDGUARD ]

Step 12: Go Back to General Settings
         Click the "General settings" tab.

Step 13: Enable SquidGuard
         Now check the "Enable" checkbox.

Step 14: Click Apply
         Click the "Apply" button (NOT just Save).
         SquidGuard service state changes:
           STOPPED --> STARTED

         IMPORTANT: You must click APPLY (not just Save) for
                    SquidGuard changes to take effect.

RESULT: SquidGuard is now active and performing URL filtering
        on all proxy traffic through pfSense.


================================================================================
PHASE 7 : CONFIGURE SSL MAN-IN-THE-MIDDLE (HTTPS INSPECTION)
================================================================================

NOTE: SSL MitM allows Squid to decrypt, inspect, and re-encrypt HTTPS
      traffic. Without this, Squid can only see the domain name (SNI)
      not the full URL. This enables accurate content filtering on
      HTTPS sites.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

[ STEP A - CREATE INTERNAL CERTIFICATE AUTHORITY (CA) ]

Step 1 : Open Cert Manager
         Top menu --> System --> Cert. Manager

Step 2 : Go to CAs Tab
         Click the "CAs" tab. Table is empty by default.

Step 3 : Click Add
         Click [+ Add] button on the right.

Step 4 : Configure the CA
         Field                  | Value
         -----------------------|-------------------------------------------
         Descriptive name       | demo-CA
         Method                 | Create an Internal Certificate Authority
         Trust Store            | Unchecked (for now)
         Key type               | RSA
         Key Length             | 2048
         Digest Algorithm       | sha256
         Lifetime (days)        | 3650  (10 years)
         Common Name            | internal-ca
         Country Code           | IN
         State or Province      | MH
         City                   | PN
         Organization           | demo
         Organizational Unit    | labs

Step 5 : Save the CA
         Click Save.
         "demo-CA" now appears in the CAs list as self-signed.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

[ STEP B - ENABLE HTTPS INTERCEPTION IN SQUID ]

Step 6 : Open Squid General Settings
         Services --> Squid Proxy Server --> General tab
         Scroll down to "SSL Man in the Middle Filtering" section.

Step 7 : Enable HTTPS/SSL Interception
         Check the box: "Enable SSL filtering" (HTTPS/SSL Interception)

Step 8 : Configure SSL MitM Fields
         Field                         | Value
         ------------------------------|--------------------------------------
         SSL/MITM Mode                 | Splice Whitelist, Bump Otherwise
         SSL Intercept Interface(s)    | LAN
         SSL Proxy Port                | 3129 (default)
         SSL Proxy Compatibility Mode  | Modern
         DHParams Key Size             | 2048 (default)
         CA                            | demo-CA (select from dropdown)
         Remote Cert Checks            | Do not verify remote certificate
         Certificate Adapt             | Select ALL options:
                                       |   - Sets the "Not After" (setValidAfter)
                                       |   - Sets the "Not Before" (setValidBefore)
                                       |   - Sets CN property (setCommonName)

Step 9 : Save
         Click Save.
         Squid will now perform SSL inspection on HTTPS traffic from LAN.

IMPORTANT NOTE FOR CLIENTS:
         Client machines on the LAN MUST import the demo-CA certificate
         into their browser's trusted root store. Otherwise every HTTPS
         site will show a certificate warning.
         Steps to export CA cert:
           System --> Cert. Manager --> CAs --> Export CA (download icon)
           Then install it in the client browser's trusted root certificates.


================================================================================
PHASE 8 : USER-BASED INTERNET ACCESS CONTROL
================================================================================

NOTE: Squid supports user authentication. When enabled, all browsers
      must present a username/password before internet access is
      granted. pfSense's local user database is used here.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

[ STEP A - ENABLE AUTHENTICATION ]

Step 1 : Open Squid Authentication Tab
         Services --> Squid Proxy Server --> "Authentication" tab

Step 2 : Select Authentication Method
         Under "Squid Authentication General Settings"
         Dropdown --> Select "Local"

Step 3 : Save
         Click Save.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

[ STEP B - CREATE PROXY USERS ]

Step 4 : Go to Users Tab
         Services --> Squid Proxy Server --> "Users" tab

Step 5 : Click Add
         Click [+ Add] to create a new proxy user.

Step 6 : Fill in User Details
         Field        | Value (Example)
         -------------|---------------------
         Username     | labuser1
         Password     | P@ssw0rd123
         Description  | Lab Student Account

Step 7 : Save the User
         Click Save.
         Repeat Steps 5-7 for each additional user.

Step 8 : Test Authentication
         On the client VM configure browser proxy settings:
           Proxy server : 192.168.148.10
           Port         : 3128
         When accessing a website a username/password popup appears.
         Use the credentials created above.

RESULT: User-based internet access is now active.
        Only authenticated users can browse the internet
        through the pfSense proxy.


================================================================================
COMPLETE ARCHITECTURE SUMMARY
================================================================================

Component           | Role                                    | Port / Location
--------------------|------------------------------------------|------------------------
pfSense Firewall    | NAT, packet filtering, WAN/LAN routing  | VM - 2 NICs
Squid Proxy         | HTTP/HTTPS proxy, logging, caching      | TCP 3128 (HTTP/3129 SSL)
SquidGuard          | URL filtering via blacklists             | Plugin to Squid
SSL MitM (CA)       | HTTPS inspection & content filtering    | Internal CA: demo-CA
User Auth (Local)   | Username/password gate for internet     | Squid local user DB
Blacklist (UT1)     | Pre-categorised URL block list          | /var/db/squidguard


================================================================================
QUICK REFERENCE - pfSense CONSOLE MENU OPTIONS
================================================================================

  0)  Logout (SSH only)         9)  pfTop
  1)  Assign Interfaces         10) Filter Logs
  2)  Set Interface(s) IP       11) Restart webConfigurator
  3)  Reset WebGUI Password     12) PHP shell + pfSense tools
  4)  Reset to Factory Defaults 13) Update from Console
  5)  Reboot System             14) Enable Secure Shell (sshd)
  6)  Halt System               15) Restore Recent Configuration
  7)  Ping Host                 16) Restart PHP-FPM
  8)  Shell

  Use option 2 to set LAN/WAN IP addresses from console.


================================================================================
IMPORTANT PORTS REFERENCE
================================================================================

  Service               | Port  | Protocol
  ----------------------|-------|----------
  pfSense WebGUI (HTTPS)| 443   | TCP
  Squid HTTP Proxy      | 3128  | TCP
  Squid SSL Proxy       | 3129  | TCP
  DNS                   | 53    | UDP/TCP
  NTP                   | 123   | UDP
  SSH (if enabled)      | 22    | TCP


================================================================================
DEFAULT CREDENTIALS (CHANGE IMMEDIATELY IN PRODUCTION)
================================================================================

  Service         | Username | Password
  ----------------|----------|----------
  pfSense WebGUI  | admin    | pfsense
  Squid Proxy     | (created | (manually)
                  |  manually|

